- Author!
- Author!

45
00:03:23,168 --> 00:03:25,848
- Bravo!
- Bravo!

46
00:03:36,851 --> 00:03:39,132
Your table is ready, Monsieur Fink.

47
00:03:39,212 --> 00:03:42,493
In fact, several members of your party
have already arrived.

48
00:03:42,573 --> 00:03:43,934
Is Garland Stanford here?

49
00:03:44,013 --> 00:03:46,854
He called to say
he'd be a few minutes late.

50
00:03:46,934 --> 00:03:48,735
Ah, here we are.

51
00:03:48,815 --> 00:03:51,655
Barton!
Barton, so glad you could make it.

52
00:03:51,736 --> 00:03:53,536
You know Richard St. Claire

53
00:03:53,616 --> 00:03:55,136
and Poppy Carnahan.

54
00:03:55,216 --> 00:03:57,297
Charmed, charmed, charmed.

55
00:03:57,377 --> 00:03:59,817
We're drinking champagne
in honor of the occasion.

56
00:03:59,818 --> 00:04:01,938
Have you seen the Herald?

57
00:04:02,018 --> 00:04:03,099
Not yet.

58
00:04:03,178 --> 00:04:04,419
I won't embarrass you,

59
00:04:04,499 --> 00:04:06,499
but Caven could
hardly contain himself.

60
00:04:06,580 --> 00:04:07,619
More important,

61
00:04:07,620 --> 00:04:09,820
Richard and Poppy here loved the play.

62
00:04:09,900 --> 00:04:10,941
Weeping.

63
00:04:11,020 --> 00:04:11,980
Copious tears.

64
00:04:11,981 --> 00:04:14,021
What did the Herald say?

65
00:04:14,102 --> 00:04:15,380
I happen to have it.

66
00:04:15,381 --> 00:04:16,381
Please, Derek...

67
00:04:16,382 --> 00:04:17,782
"Bare Ruined Choirs:

68
00:04:17,823 --> 00:04:20,223
Triumph of the Common Man.

69
00:04:20,263 --> 00:04:22,383
The star of Bare Ruined Choirs

70
00:04:22,464 --> 00:04:24,664
was nowhere seen
on the stage last night,

71
00:04:24,744 --> 00:04:26,984
though the thespians
acquitted themselves admirably.

72
00:04:26,985 --> 00:04:28,666
The find of the evening

73
00:04:28,745 --> 00:04:31,586
was the author of this drama
about simple folk,

74
00:04:31,666 --> 00:04:33,027
fishmongers, in fact,

75
00:04:33,067 --> 00:04:34,747
whose brute struggle for existence

76
00:04:34,787 --> 00:04:37,308
cannot quite quell their longing
for something higher.

77
00:04:37,388 --> 00:04:38,788
The playwright finds nobility

78
00:04:38,828 --> 00:04:40,548
in the most squalid corners

79
00:04:40,628 --> 00:04:43,149
and poetry in the most callous speech.

80
00:04:43,229 --> 00:04:46,109
A tough new voice
in the American theater has arrived,

81
00:04:46,190 --> 00:04:48,551
and the owner of that voice is named...

82
00:04:48,590 --> 00:04:50,471
Barton Fink."

83
00:04:50,511 --> 00:04:54,112
They'll be wrapping fish in it
in the morning.

84
00:04:54,152 --> 00:04:55,872
Cynic.

85
00:04:55,953 --> 00:04:58,473
I can't start listening to the critics,

86
00:04:58,553 --> 00:05:01,354
and I can't kid myself
about my own work.

87
00:05:01,394 --> 00:05:03,274
A writer writes from his gut.

88
00:05:03,314 --> 00:05:06,155
His gut tells him
what's good and what's...

89
00:05:06,235 --> 00:05:08,075
merely adequate.

90
00:05:09,236 --> 00:05:12,077
I don't pretend to be a critic,

91
00:05:12,117 --> 00:05:14,557
but Lord knows I have a gut,

92
00:05:14,638 --> 00:05:17,958
and my gut tells me it's simply...

93
00:05:18,039 --> 00:05:20,039
marvelous.

94
00:05:20,079 --> 00:05:22,320
And a charming gut it is.

95
00:05:22,400 --> 00:05:24,160
Oh, you dog.

96
00:05:24,241 --> 00:05:26,200
Aroo!

97
00:05:26,281 --> 00:05:27,561
Oh, stop.

98
00:05:32,802 --> 00:05:35,603
I thought you were going to join us.

99
00:05:35,643 --> 00:05:38,604
Jesus, Garland,
you left me alone with those people?

100
00:05:38,644 --> 00:05:39,763
Don't panic.

101
00:05:39,764 --> 00:05:41,805
I'll join you in a minute.

102
00:05:41,845 --> 00:05:44,325
We have to talk a little business.

103
00:05:44,406 --> 00:05:47,206
I've just been on the phone
to Los Angeles.

104
00:05:47,287 --> 00:05:50,087
Barton, Capitol Pictures wants to
put you under contract.

105
00:05:50,167 --> 00:05:52,488
They've offered you $1,000 a week.

106
00:05:52,568 --> 00:05:55,369
I think I can get them
to go as high as 2.

107
00:05:55,448 --> 00:05:56,728
To do what?

108
00:05:56,729 --> 00:05:58,849
What do you do for a living?

109
00:05:58,930 --> 00:06:00,650
I'm not sure anymore.

110
00:06:00,730 --> 00:06:03,971
I guess I try to make a difference.

111
00:06:04,050 --> 00:06:06,971
There's no pressure here
because I respect you,

112
00:06:07,052 --> 00:06:09,172
but a brief tenure in Hollywood

113
00:06:09,212 --> 00:06:11,332
could support you through the writing

114
00:06:11,413 --> 00:06:13,094
of any number of plays.

115
00:06:13,173 --> 00:06:14,533
I don't know, Garland.

116
00:06:14,613 --> 00:06:16,734
My place is here right now.

117
00:06:16,814 --> 00:06:19,455
I feel I'm on the brink of success.

118
00:06:19,535 --> 00:06:21,736
I'd say you're already enjoying some.

119
00:06:21,815 --> 00:06:23,336
No. Don't you see?

120
00:06:23,416 --> 00:06:26,176
Not the kind of success
where critics fawn over you

121
00:06:26,257 --> 00:06:28,897
or producers like Derek
make a lot of money.

122
00:06:28,978 --> 00:06:30,698
No. A real success.

123
00:06:30,778 --> 00:06:32,738
The success we've been dreaming about...

124
00:06:32,819 --> 00:06:35,619
the creation of a new living theater

125
00:06:35,699 --> 00:06:38,580
of and about and for the common man.

126
00:06:38,660 --> 00:06:41,021
If I ran off to Hollywood now,

127
00:06:41,061 --> 00:06:42,421
I'd be making money,

128
00:06:42,501 --> 00:06:44,261
going to parties,
meeting the big shots,

129
00:06:44,342 --> 00:06:46,021
but I'd be cutting myself off

130
00:06:46,102 --> 00:06:48,303
from the wellspring of that success,

131
00:06:48,382 --> 00:06:49,903
from the common man.

132
00:06:51,943 --> 00:06:55,585
Oh, I guess I'm spouting off again.

133
00:06:55,625 --> 00:06:57,305
You see Caven's review?

134
00:06:57,385 --> 00:06:58,985
No. What did it say?

135
00:06:59,065 --> 00:07:00,466
Here, take my copy.

136
00:07:00,546 --> 00:07:02,306
You're the toast of Broadway,

137
00:07:02,347 --> 00:07:04,067
and you have an opportunity

138
00:07:04,107 --> 00:07:07,388
to redeem that for a little cash...

139
00:07:07,467 --> 00:07:09,628
Strike that.
A lot of cash.

140
00:07:09,708 --> 00:07:14,469
The common man will still be here
when you get back.

141
00:07:14,550 --> 00:07:15,910
Who knows?

142
00:07:15,949 --> 00:07:19,271
They may even have one or two of them
out in Hollywood.

143
00:07:19,311 --> 00:07:21,831
That's a rationalization, Garland.

144
00:07:21,912 --> 00:07:26,073
Barton, it was a joke.

145
00:08:47,934 --> 00:08:50,495
Welcome to Hotel Earle.
May I help you?

146
00:08:50,535 --> 00:08:51,936
I'm checking in.

147
00:08:51,975 --> 00:08:53,215
Barton Fink.

148
00:08:53,256 --> 00:08:55,777
All righty.

149
00:08:57,336 --> 00:08:59,297
Okay...

150
00:08:59,378 --> 00:09:01,538
F-I-N-K?

151
00:09:04,139 --> 00:09:05,298
"Fink, Barton."

152
00:09:05,299 --> 00:09:06,699
That must be you, huh?

153
00:09:06,780 --> 00:09:07,779
Must be.

154
00:09:07,860 --> 00:09:12,261
Okay, then everything
seems to be in order.

155
00:09:12,341 --> 00:09:15,301
Everything seems to be in order.

156
00:09:15,382 --> 00:09:16,582
Just...

157
00:09:17,782 --> 00:09:20,463
Are you a trans or a res?

158
00:09:20,543 --> 00:09:21,584
Excuse me?

159
00:09:21,663 --> 00:09:23,143
Transient or resident?

160
00:09:23,224 --> 00:09:24,264
I...

161
00:09:24,344 --> 00:09:26,225
I... I... I don't know.

162
00:09:26,265 --> 00:09:28,385
I mean, I'll be here indefinitely.

163
00:09:28,465 --> 00:09:31,186
Res. That's 25.50 a week
payable in advance.

164
00:09:31,266 --> 00:09:32,906
Check-out time's 12:00 sharp,

165
00:09:32,987 --> 00:09:34,827
only forget that.
You're a res.

166
00:09:34,867 --> 00:09:36,026
If you need anything,
pick up your personal in-room telephone.

167
00:09:36,027 --> 00:09:37,987
If you need anything,
pick up your personal in-room telephone.

168
00:09:37,988 --> 00:09:39,267
My name is Chet.

169
00:09:39,268 --> 00:09:40,628
Although we provide privacy

170
00:09:40,669 --> 00:09:42,068
for the residential guests,

171
00:09:42,149 --> 00:09:43,789
we're a full-service hotel,

172
00:09:43,869 --> 00:09:45,109
including complimentary shoe shine.

173
00:09:45,190 --> 00:09:46,710
My name is Chet.

174
00:09:48,230 --> 00:09:49,391
Okay.

175
00:09:54,392 --> 00:09:56,192
Those your only bags?

176
00:09:56,273 --> 00:09:59,194
The others are being sent.

177
00:09:59,273 --> 00:10:02,194
Welcome to Los Angeles, Mr. Fink.

178
00:10:13,998 --> 00:10:15,397
Six, please.

179
00:10:18,478 --> 00:10:21,479
Next stop... six.

180
00:10:28,881 --> 00:10:31,402
This stop... six.

181
00:13:25,809 --> 00:13:27,689
Is that him?

182
00:13:27,729 --> 00:13:30,890
Is that Barton Fink?

183
00:13:30,929 --> 00:13:32,290
Let me at him.

184
00:13:32,370 --> 00:13:34,890
Let me put my arms
around this guy.

185
00:13:34,931 --> 00:13:36,811
Let me hug this guy.

186
00:13:36,851 --> 00:13:38,772
How the hell are ya?

187
00:13:38,812 --> 00:13:39,812
Good trip?

188
00:13:39,892 --> 00:13:41,293
My name's Jack Lipnick.

189
00:13:41,332 --> 00:13:43,133
You know that.
You read the papers.

190
00:13:43,213 --> 00:13:44,854
Lou treating you all right?

191
00:13:44,933 --> 00:13:47,054
What's the matter
with your face?

192
00:13:47,134 --> 00:13:49,375
What's the matter
with his face, Lou?

193
00:13:49,454 --> 00:13:50,775
It's not so bad.

194
00:13:50,855 --> 00:13:52,775
A mosquito in my room.

195
00:13:52,855 --> 00:13:54,094
Where'd we put him?

196
00:13:54,095 --> 00:13:55,416
I'm at the Earle.

197
00:13:55,496 --> 00:13:57,817
Never heard of it.
Let's move him.

198
00:13:57,897 --> 00:13:59,176
Stay at my place.

199
00:13:59,177 --> 00:14:00,697
I wanted a place a little less...

200
00:14:00,778 --> 00:14:03,178
Less Hollywood. Say it.
It's not a dirty word.

201
00:14:03,259 --> 00:14:05,218
Say whatever you want.

202
00:14:05,299 --> 00:14:07,739
The writer is king
at Capitol Pictures.

203
00:14:07,819 --> 00:14:09,020
Look at your paycheck.

204
00:14:09,100 --> 00:14:11,100
That's what
we think of writers.

205
00:14:11,180 --> 00:14:13,981
So, what kind of pictures
does he like?

206
00:14:14,061 --> 00:14:16,582
Mr. Fink hasn't given
a preference, Mr. Lipnick.

207
00:14:16,662 --> 00:14:18,662
So, how about it, Bart?

208
00:14:18,743 --> 00:14:20,583
Well, uh, to be honest,

209
00:14:20,663 --> 00:14:23,264
I don't go to the pictures much.

210
00:14:23,343 --> 00:14:24,383
That's okay.

211
00:14:24,384 --> 00:14:26,025
You probably
walked in here

212
00:14:26,104 --> 00:14:28,545
thinking that was going
to be a handicap,

213
00:14:28,625 --> 00:14:31,425
thinking we wanted people
who knew something about the medium,

214
00:14:31,506 --> 00:14:33,945
thinking there's technical
mumbo jumbo to learn.

215
00:14:33,946 --> 00:14:35,427
You were dead wrong.

216
00:14:35,507 --> 00:14:38,588
There's only one thing...
Can you tell a story?

217
00:14:38,628 --> 00:14:40,788
Can you make us laugh,
make us cry,

218
00:14:40,868 --> 00:14:43,309
make us want
to break out in song?

219
00:14:43,389 --> 00:14:44,709
That more than one thing?

220
00:14:44,789 --> 00:14:47,670
I run this dump, and I don't know
technical mumbo jumbo.

221
00:14:47,790 --> 00:14:49,270
Why do I run it?

222
00:14:49,351 --> 00:14:51,711
'Cause I got horse sense, showmanship!

223
00:14:51,751 --> 00:14:54,432
And also I'm bigger
and meaner and louder

224
00:14:54,472 --> 00:14:56,753
than any other kike
in this town.

225
00:14:56,832 --> 00:14:59,193
I don't mean my dick's
bigger than yours.

226
00:14:59,273 --> 00:15:01,593
It's not a sexual thing.
Coffee?

227
00:15:04,074 --> 00:15:05,475
Yes, thank you.

228
00:15:05,555 --> 00:15:06,475
Lou!

229
00:15:13,677 --> 00:15:16,478
Used to have shares
in the company,

230
00:15:16,518 --> 00:15:17,637
ownership interest,

231
00:15:17,638 --> 00:15:20,118
got bought out...
muscled out.

232
00:15:20,199 --> 00:15:22,999
We keep him around.
He's got a family.

233
00:15:23,080 --> 00:15:24,359
Poor schmuck.
He's sensitive.

234
00:15:24,400 --> 00:15:26,640
Don't mention the old days.
Hell, say whatever you want.

235
00:15:26,641 --> 00:15:28,041
Look, barring a preference,

236
00:15:28,080 --> 00:15:30,922
you'll be working on
a wrestling picture... Wallace Beery.

237
00:15:30,961 --> 00:15:33,803
They say you know
the poetry of the street.

238
00:15:33,882 --> 00:15:35,643
That rules out
westerns, pirates,

239
00:15:35,723 --> 00:15:37,483
screwball, Bible, Roman...

240
00:15:37,563 --> 00:15:39,964
I'm not some guy
that thinks poetic is fruity.

241
00:15:40,044 --> 00:15:41,404
We're together on that.

242
00:15:41,485 --> 00:15:43,325
I'm from New York myself.

243
00:15:43,405 --> 00:15:46,246
Minsk... if you want
to go all the way back,

244
00:15:46,286 --> 00:15:48,806
which we won't
if you don't mind.

245
00:15:48,887 --> 00:15:50,527
People will say to you...

246
00:15:50,607 --> 00:15:53,128
Wallace Beery, wrestling...
it's a B picture.

247
00:15:53,168 --> 00:15:54,528
You tell them... bullshit!

248
00:15:54,608 --> 00:15:57,649
We don't make B pictures
here at Capitol.

249
00:15:57,689 --> 00:16:00,889
Let's put a stop
to that rumor right now.

250
00:16:04,531 --> 00:16:05,650
Thanks, Lou.

251
00:16:05,651 --> 00:16:07,051
Join us.
Join us.

252
00:16:07,131 --> 00:16:09,772
We're talking about
the Wally Beery picture.

253
00:16:09,812 --> 00:16:11,413
Excellent picture.

254
00:16:11,452 --> 00:16:13,653
Got a treatment on it yet?

255
00:16:13,733 --> 00:16:15,333
We just bought the story.

256
00:16:15,413 --> 00:16:16,814
Saturday Evening Post.

257
00:16:16,854 --> 00:16:18,214
The hell with the story.

258
00:16:18,294 --> 00:16:19,495
Wally Beery's a wrestler.

259
00:16:19,574 --> 00:16:21,775
Give me his hopes, his dreams.

260
00:16:21,815 --> 00:16:24,616
Naturally he gets mixed up
with a bad element

261
00:16:24,696 --> 00:16:27,417
and a romantic interest
or else an orphan.

262
00:16:27,496 --> 00:16:31,018
Lou, think Wally's too old
for a romantic interest?

263
00:16:33,938 --> 00:16:35,178
Look at me.

264
00:16:35,259 --> 00:16:37,139
A writer in the room,

265
00:16:37,179 --> 00:16:39,780
and I'm asking Lou
about the goddamn story.

266
00:16:39,860 --> 00:16:41,181
Which is it, Bart?

267
00:16:41,260 --> 00:16:43,621
Orphan?
Dame?

